name: The Talis River
description:
The crystal waters of this river come from the plains and mountains to
the north as clear and gelid as any in Shalar.  By the time they reach
southern Cimar, they've taken a slightly amber hue, and are noticeably more
opaque than at the northern end of town, but are still relatively clean and
healthy waters.  The tiny bubbles and distortions in the water's seemingly
peaceful surface belie the illusion of placidity by speeding downstream at
an impressive pace.  Near the South Bridge, the water finally begins to
stir, and as it reaches the southern portcullis, it tumbles into rapids as
it topples over a waterfall to crash into the ocean's shore below.  Here at
the northern portcullis, however, the still-smooth waters slip through the
iron bars quietly.

name: A Narrow Alleyway
description:
This dark alley is nestled between the inner wall of Cimar and a dark
building to your west.  Frightening sounds and smells waft to you from that
direction as you pass.  Treading carefully, you step around what seems upon
prodding to be the bloated corpse of an unidentifiable rodent.  The stench
from whatever fetid raunch has spilled itself about rises as your shuffling
feet disturb its home, and your nostrils try to close themselves off.  To
no avail, however, as it merely penetrates your nasal cavity further.  A
rustling sound to one side draws your attention, and you begin to wonder
what warrants your presence in this darkened alley.

name: A Narrow Alleyway
description:
This dark alley is nestled between the inner wall of Cimar and a dark
building to your west.  Frightening sounds and smells waft to you from that
direction as you pass.  Treading carefully, you step around what seems upon

rustling sound to one side draws your attention, and you begin to wonder
what warrants your presence in this darkened alley.

name: The Obsidian Shrine
description:
Everything in this room is made of the blackest stone you've ever seen.
A square column of the light-absorbing rock stands at each corner, and the
door is framed with wide slabs of it.  The floor and even the ceiling are
pieced together with massive squares of obsidian, and a large table-like
structure in the center of the room is its only embellishment - also
crafted of black stone.  The table has deep gouges along the top, running
down the edges to hollowed out sections at each corner.  Weathered leather
straps and metal chains and hooks garnish it about every face, and appear
to be the only non-obsidian items in the room.  Gaping at the table and its
accompanying implements, you can only imagine what its full use might be.
To the south is another darkened doorway.

name: The Obsidian Monolith
description:
This is the room where necromancers from all over Shalar come to meet and
refine their abilities in the dark arts.  Cimar's necromancer guild is
known around the world, and glancing about this room, you can tell why.
The quality of the glass golems of the necromancers here shows in the way
the bloody light from a torch in the corner refracts through their bodies,
and the intricate detail in the hex dolls hanging from the walls is
magnificent.  Ruddy streams of daylight peer in around the guildhall's
obsidian monolith where it punctures the ceiling.  And what stands against
the western wall, but a route through which necromancers might escape to
the river from the torch-wielding mobs that come knocking!  Truly, this is
one of the finest guilds you've ever seen.

name: The Army Barracks
description:
These are the well kept quarters of 200 men.  One might expect to be
overpowered by earthy smells in such a place, but you are pleasantly
surprised to find no odor.  The Cimarrite Army is a highly trained militia,
extensively educated, intensively disciplined, and apparently well fed and
cared for.  Each unoccupied bed is carefully made, and every shelf holds
its books, maps, personal items, and toiletries in an orderly fashion.  As
is its practice, the Army has devoted one quarter of its number to
patrolling the city to guard against external and internal threats to the
peace, rather than leave such weighty matters to Cimar's incompetent
Watchmen.  A large banner overhead reads:  -The Dragon Troop-

name: New Cimar
description:
You stand in the strip of homes and plots of land between Cimar's outer
and inner walls.  It's known as New Cimar in polite circles, and sometimes
as Leechtown or Fungusville in impolite ones.  It houses some of the lesser
families of Cimar, in their smaller homes and less extravagant businesses,
but also holds in its confines the powerful and world-renown mage guilds of
Cimar and the highly trained Cimarrite Army.  For now, though, these things
are at the back of your mind as you kick your way through the litter and
debris.  To your north is Toller Road, and immediately west is the inner
wall.  East of here is one of the tents occupied by the Army.

description:

debris.  A ways off to the north is Toller Road, and immediately west is
the inner wall.  East of here is one of the tents occupied by the Army.

name: New Cimar
description:
You stand in the strip of homes and plots of land between Cimar's outer
and inner walls.  It's known as New Cimar in polite circles, and sometimes
as Leechtown or Fungusville in impolite ones.  It houses some of the lesser
families of Cimar, in their smaller homes and less extravagant businesses,
but also holds in its confines the powerful and world-renown mage guilds of
Cimar and the highly trained Cimarrite Army.  For now, though, these things
are at the back of your mind as you kick your way through the litter and
debris.  Immediately to your west is the inner wall.  East of here is one
of the tents occupied by the Army.  South lies East Rantid Road.

name: The Southeastern Arch
description:
This arch, one of five in Cimar, is the portal through which Rantid Road
spills into the wilderness beyond the city's great walls.  The southern
arches are smaller and less staggeringly impressive overall, but still
serve their purpose admirably.  From this point in the city, you can see
Rantid Road stretching to the west, across a river and into what looks to
be a bustling business district of some sort.  Dominating the sky to the
northwest is Mount Cim, thrusting upward into the atmosphere, where it
punctures the cloud cover and continues toward the heavens.  Below you, the
stones are worn through to a far older rock layer beneath.  East lie the
outskirts of Cimar.

name: East Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has
expanded, and since the advent of highways and trade routes, Rantid Road
has fallen into a state of relative disuse.  Compared with the incredible
traffic of Toller Road, this street is calm and picturesque.  The
cobblestones making up the road are worn and cracked at the edges, and make
a uniform surface of smoothed stone.  In the center, the cobblestones have
come entirely away in many places, revealing occasional glimpses at the
ancient slate pathways which preceded even Old Cimar.  The road continues
to the west through the inner wall and into the center of Old Cimar.  To
the east is the south-east gate of Cimar, and to the north and south lies
New Cimar.

name: East Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has
expanded, and since the advent of highways and trade routes, Rantid Road
has fallen into a state of relative disuse.  Compared with the incredible

a uniform surface of smoothed stone.  In the center, the cobblestones have
come entirely away in many places, revealing occasional glimpses at the
ancient slate pathways which preceded even Old Cimar.  The road is very
wide here, and continues either to the east through the inner wall, or west
into the center of Old Cimar.  To your south, a dark alley beckons.

wide here, and continues to the west into the center of Old Cimar.  North
of you, a dark and foreboding alleyway beckons to the adventuresome or
careless.

name: East Rantid Road
description:

settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has

ancient slate pathways which preceded even Old Cimar.  Rantid Road
continues to the west, across the South Bridge and into the center of Old
Cimar.  The expansive road lies east and north of you.

name: The South Bridge
description:
Huge old steelwood beams, as thick as an abyss titan's leg and as smooth
as an elf's posterior, make up the South Bridge and allow Rantid Road to
pass over the Talis River.  The river swells here, running high toward the
waterfall to the south, and the bridge is barely a foot above water level.
You feel no hazard, though, as passing horses, carriages and titans do not
even cause the beams beneath you to shudder slightly.  The edge of the
bridge is to your north, guarded by sturdy handrails, and you can see the
other edge of this very wide bridge ten yards off to the south.  East of
you lies Rantid Road, and the bridge continues to the west.

name: The Talis River
description:
The crystal waters of this river come from the plains and mountains to
the north as clear and gelid as any in Shalar.  By the time they reach
southern Cimar, they've taken a slightly amber hue, and are noticeably more
opaque than at the northern end of town, but are still relatively clean and
healthy waters.  Here, behind the infamous Cimar necromancer guild, is
where most of the pollution comes from.  The tiny bubbles and distortions
in the water's seemingly peaceful surface belie the illusion of placidity
by speeding downstream at an impressive pace.  Near the South Bridge, the
water finally begins to stir, and as it reaches the southern portcullis, it
tumbles into rapids as it topples over a waterfall to crash into the
ocean's shore below.  The South Bridge is immediately to your south.

name: Godein Avenue
description:
Everywhere on this street, people rush to be where they aren't and shove
one another out of the way to get there.  There are a few scattered homes
to either side of the road, but they've been pushed to the side and crushed
into submission by the large guilds to your west.  The traffic on this
street, you now see, is mostly of the arcane and magical sort;  the
occasional sound of a roaring animal or the deafening crack of instantly
frozen water fizzle and pop through the air as you walk.  Turning your
attention to the guilds themselves, you see that they are stacked atop one
another and clustered together in odd formation, strange flashes of light
emitting occasionally from certain windows.  You shiver to think that
within those walls lurk the ability to summon the elements, to change
shape, to divine the bleak sense behind all of creation, weave it together
into a logical progression, and understand what the gods have done with
this world.

name: A Quiet Residence
description:
The dim lighting in this room makes it difficult to tell what sort of
furnishings there are, but you can see well enough to avoid them as you
walk through.  It looks to be a fairly well-off place;  certainly, the
ceiling and walls aren't caving in, and the floor is level.  The windows
let in a significant amount of light, and you can see that the panes of
glass are clean and new, unwarped by time, and free of any spidering
cracks.  Once you take in the quaint home visually, you note the fact that
there is very little noise here.  Near the intersection of Rantid Road and
Godein Avenue, there isn't all that much traffic.  The occasional muffled
explosion wafts on the air from across the street, but otherwise it is
pleasantly still.

name: A Darkened Alley
description:
This dark alley is nestled between the inner wall of Cimar and the back
wall of a private home to your west.  Treading carefully, you step around
what seems upon prodding to be the bloated corpse of an unidentifiable
rodent.  The stench from whatever fetid raunch has spilled itself about
rises as your shuffling feet disturb its home, and your nostrils try to
close themselves off.  To no avail, however, as it merely penetrates your
nasal cavity further.  A rustling sound to one side draws your attention,
and you begin to wonder what warrants your presence in this darkened alley.
The relative safety of New Cimar is to the south.

name: The Middle of an Alley
description:
This dark alley is nestled between the inner wall of Cimar and the back
wall of a private home to your west.  You stand in its center being slowly
digested by the utter darkness around you.  Visible to your north and south
are distant pictures of the friendly streets of Cimar, as though viewed
from across a chasm.  This part of the alley is very quiet, absent of all
sounds but the quiet dripping of water and occasional peaceful rustle of a
rodent or large insect.  Even the noise of the bustling city is muffled,
almost entirely dampened, by the walls and piles of trash around you.  Most
would never think of an alley as such a therapeutic environment.

rises as your shuffling feet disturb its home, and your nostrils try to
close themselves off.  To no avail, however, as it merely penetrates your
nasal cavity further.  A rustling sound to one side draws your attention,
and you begin to wonder what warrants your presence in this darkened alley.
The safety of Rantid Road lies to the north.

name: New Cimar
description:
You stand in the strip of homes and plots of land between Cimar's outer
and inner walls.  It's known as New Cimar in polite circles, and sometimes
as Leechtown or Fungusville in impolite ones.  It houses some of the lesser
families of Cimar, in their smaller homes and less extravagant businesses,
but also holds in its confines the powerful and world-renown mage guilds of
Cimar and the highly trained Cimarrite Army.  For now, though, these things
are at the back of your mind as you kick your way through the litter and
debris.  Immediately to your west is the inner wall.  East of here, a
private residence is nestled inside the massive outer wall.  North lies
East Rantid Road, and to the south you can continue through New Cimar.

To the north and south, New Cimar continues.

a private home wraps around the corner of the road, piled into the corner
of the outer wall.

private home is nestled beneath the towering outer wall of the city.
Strangely, here where Godein Avenue plunges into New Cimar, a tall obsidian
monolith of some sort stands perfectly nonsensically in the road.

debris.  To the north, the mage block is accessible by a small gate in the
inner wall, and to your east and west, you can continue through New Cimar.
To the south, a short road leads to a strange door, which in turn leads
to thin air over a sudden cliff.

name: New Cimar
description:
You stand in the strip of homes and plots of land between Cimar's outer
and inner walls.  It's known as New Cimar in polite circles, and sometimes
as Leechtown or Fungusville in impolite ones.  It houses some of the lesser

debris.  To the north, the mage block is accessible by a small gate in the
inner wall, and to your east and west, you can continue through New Cimar.
To the south, a beautiful shining hall of crystal awaits, appearing fairly
incongruous in New Cimar.

name: New Cimar
description:
You stand in the strip of homes and plots of land between Cimar's outer
and inner walls.  It's known as New Cimar in polite circles, and sometimes
as Leechtown or Fungusville in impolite ones.  It houses some of the lesser
families of Cimar, in their smaller homes and less extravagant businesses,
but also holds in its confines the powerful and world-renown mage guilds of
Cimar and the highly trained Cimarrite Army.  For now, though, these things
are at the back of your mind as you kick your way through the litter and
debris.  To the north, the inner wall of Cimar makes ready to cross the
Talis River by way of a grand arch, while the outer wall does much the same
in a far grander fashion a bit to the south.  Between here and the outer
wall lies a large, exquisite home.  To your west, a small bridge crosses
the river, and to the east lies New Cimar.

name: The Leap of Faith
description:
Standing here, you find that you can see directly through a gate in the
outer wall and stare straight across the sea.  To either side of you, homes
are set against the massive wall, but this short spurt of a road opens between
them to this inexplicable door... leading to thin air.  Looking over the edge
of the street, you see a twenty or thirty foot drop down a sheer cliff to the
rocky shore below.  Salty, reddish water churns itself into a thick and almost
blood-like foam far below your feet, and it's easy to feel slightly
disoriented staring down in this fashion.  Turning your focus back out to the
crimson sea past your cliff, you squint but cannot discern much through the
ocean mist cutting off perception a few miles off the shore.  The close
proximity of the mage block implies that this gate is used to test magical
flying abilities in a trial by fire.

name: A Pleasant Home
description:
This hut-like dwelling seems not to have had its life choked from it by
the surroundings, like many other homes in New Cimar.  Unfazed by the
constant noise, the stench, the litter, and cityguards and soldiers running
about, its inhabitants look to be quite happy.  An expensive looking carpet
covers the entire floor, and quality lamps dangle from each corner of the
ceiling.  A dresser is posed in one corner, with a very well formed clay
pot and basin for washing.  The windows even look new, unblemished, and
free of fractures.  Given what you know about the rest of New Cimar, it's
quite remarkable that someone with enough money to put together such a home
would bother to do it here.  To your west, the door leads back out into the
city.

name: A Small Home
description:
This modest dwelling is where someone new to Cimar has made his or her
home.  Nestled inside Cimar's massive outer wall, it's right in the middle
of the rather undesirable plot of land which is New Cimar;  between the
cityguard headquarters and the army's barracks however, there's very little
traffic, creating a surprisingly relaxed environment.  Looking around, you
note dozens - perhaps hundreds - of personal affects strewn about,
decorating every possible flat surface.  The walls are covered with
paintings and maps, the tabletops and shelves are buried under delicate
porcelain and rough hewn dolls.  To the north is a quiet bedroom.

name: A Quiet Bedroom
description:
This unassuming bedchamber is dimly lit by candles at each side of the
head of the bed.  The wall to the east is cracked for the entire floor-to-
ceiling length, and cold air flows in through the gap from the tight cool
space between walls.  As a result, the room is pleasantly cool despite the
sometimes oppressive heat of New Cimar's activity.  The bed is simple but
appears quite comfortable, with ragged and patched sheets covering it.  A
very few personal affects adorn a chest of drawers with a large mirror -
which, despite its obvious wear, is quite a distinguished and expensive
thing for a denizen of New Cimar to own.  Back to the south, the rest of
the house glows warmly.  Through a hazy window to the west, you can make
out the motion of passersby on the street outside.

name: A Serene Home
description:
The peace and quiet in this comfortable yet spartan dwelling are almost
overwhelming.  Beautiful green plants adorn the walls and ceiling, draped
down to create an almost forest-like effect.  The air is warm and moist,
and reeks heavily of the sweet scent of pure oxygen.  A few plain brown
pillows rest on the floor, and a single small bookshelf sits against the
back wall.  None of the noise from outside this room intrudes within;
whether by some effect the dozens of plants produce or by a magical
enchantment, this is a perfectly quiet abode despite being across a busy
street from the mage block and right next to some very noisy and dirty
homes.

name: A Filthy Shack
description:
Piled into the corner of Cimar's huge outer wall, this tiny residence is
huddled in a forgotten part of New Cimar.  It looks as though it must house
several families - dirty families - who have erected small barriers in a
last desperate attempt to mark something as their property.  You can see
rags, but you remain unsure as to whether they are used as clothing,
bedding, or bandages for rotting lepers who now run naked and free through
the polluted streets.  Flies in the air buzz in circuitous routes, as
though avoiding the deadly hand of stench which wafts here and there
listlessly, occasionally brushing by your own nose.  From one corner, you
hear a coughing fit which subsides into restless sleep, and beneath a pile
of mildewed blankets at your feet, something rustles briefly into
consciousness, then fades back to the comforting oblivion of sleep.

name: A Raucous Home
description:
Infants and toddlers ranging widely in both age and race litter the floor
and meager furniture of this dwelling.  The bulk of the noise in this room,
though, comes from adults with too many spirits in them.  They scream and
laugh uproariously every time a fledgeling human or dwarf tumbles to the
floor and wails, and it seems that the more serious the spill taken by the
child, the louder the accompaniment of laughter.  It isn't clear where the
babies have come from, merely that they inhabit the home now.  It is
likewise uncertain what business the adults have in the room.  The first
two things that occur to you are that it might be either a neighborhood
nursery of some sort, or that you might get yourself a good price for a
newborn elf here.

name: The Mage Block
description:
Entering this area, you are assaulted from every angle by a sudden flood
of people.  People of all ages, races and creeds carom through the area,
looking for whatever they need (and will most likely find) here, in Cimar's
famous mage block.  Every type of mage, theurgist, and student presents
his or herself here, from the lowliest novice seeking words of
encouragement, to the young scholar on his way to purchase required
reagents, to the seasoned and intimidating crowd of learned magi who strut
and pose for one another in the prime of their lives.  Colors and lights
flash in mesmerizing patterns, while the din of excitement and the smell of
danger are occasionally punctuated by the explosion of some concoction or
the scream of an unhappily summoned elemental demon.

name: The Upper Foyer
description:
On this, the upper floor of the mage block, there begins to be some
distinction between types of mages one might see.  Clearly, you see fewer of
the elementalist sort.  The stench of powders and liquids is not so
overpowering.  However, you see more fur and feathers, and quite a few whole
animals.  Those who are coming in seem to be heading to the north, while those
who leave are certainly coming from that direction;  to the west, there is
very little traffic at all.  This is quiet by comparison with the rooms below
your feet.  The walls are clean in this room, and no windows mar their
surfaces.

name: The Open Ledge
description:
This is the place Cimar's shapeshifters call home.  Natural stone, or at
least something constructed to look like it, makes up a sort of cliff or
ledge which juts out from the top of the mage block.  Open air flows freely,
and sunlight beats down during the day.  A shapeshifter might freely assume
the form of a plant or animal and stay here quite happily.  In fact, many of
the plants you see here now may be quietly practicing shapeshifters.  Scorch
marks and missing chunks of stone might be attributed to elemental forms,
while most of the piles of dung are likely from the animals, one would hope.

name: The Unused Guild
description:
This is an as-yet-unoccupied guild, though recently several fellows from
the continent across the sea to the south have been eyeing up the property,
and using strange magic in full view of the mages downstairs.  Perhaps this
room will soon be put to good use.  For now, its dusty corners and
cobwebbed ceiling are a bit depressing.

name: The Elemental Tower
description:
Rising out from the mage block, this mighty tower room stands as a symbol
of ability, of power and might... of supremacy lorded over all other guilds.
The highest point in Cimar (save for its walls, the temple, and palace of
High Cimar, of course), this is quite simply the most intimidating and
impressive of structures in the city.  Elemental magics of all kinds are
practiced here;  smoke and mist fill sections of the room, while ice and
mud coat the floor in other places.  Wisps of fire and snow dance a
sophisticated tangle of a pattern through rapidly moving air, and
electricity crackles along the walls.  Powders and liquids and reagents
are in both ready supply and heavy odor.  Surely, the magic practiced in
this most pungent of rooms must be superior.

name: The Crystalline Hall
description:
Burning with the cold fire of hard clear crystal, everything in this hall
shimmers and sings the high pitched song of ageless beauty.  The walls and
ceiling are not entirely crystal and transparent;  there is a highly ornate
layer of the material covering the insides of the walls.  The solid wall
behind seems to be covered with mirrors to enhance the effect of the
crystal pillars, columns and ornaments, but you can't quite tell where the
refraction of light by the crystals ends and the reflection by a mirrored
surface beneath might begin.  Even the floor and ceiling of this room are
cold hard diamond in nature.

name: The Master's Home
description:
This room is filled with clocks of all shapes and sizes.  Staring around
in awe, you can see what must be at least a thousand of them;  nearby, a
grandfather clock the size of a titan, tiny clocks with birds for numbers,
clocks shaped like logs of wood and tin cans and even one made of a steel
plate which covers an entire wall, with six-foot-long claymores as hands.
The ticking and tocking is almost deafening, and you realize this might be
a poor place to stand at the hour.  This is the main chamber of the
dwelling of the Master;  the superintendent and landlord of the mage block
across the street.  This room is rather awe inspiring, but merely a shade
of the Master's powerful personality.

name: A Balcony
description:
This landing juts out from Cimar's outer wall and overlooks the ocean.
To the west, you can see and hear the waterfall, which is the Talis River
finally crashing down Cimar's cliff to the rocky shore of the sea below.
Above you, the massive outer wall stretches up and appears to touch the
sky;  it blots out half the stars on a clear night and keeps this balcony
in the shade for most of the day.  To your east, the red cliffs below you
stretch off along the shoreline, with the outer wall perched atop them for
quite a distance until it finally pulls away to turn north out of sight.
Leaning over the balcony's edge to peer straight down, you see the reddish
water working itself into a thick foam, crashing against the shore again
and again.

name: The Talis River
description:
The crystal waters of this river come from the plains and mountains to
the north as clear and gelid as any in Shalar.  By the time they reach
southern Cimar, they've taken a slightly amber hue, and are noticeably
more opaque than at the northern end of town, but are still relatively
clean and healthy waters.  The tiny bubbles and distortions in the
water's seemingly peaceful surface belie the illusion of placidity by
speeding downstream at an impressive pace.  Near the South Bridge, the
water finally begins to stir, and as it reaches the southern portcullis,
it tumbles into rapids as it topples over a waterfall to crash into the
ocean's shore below.  A bridge crosses the water directly to your south.

name: The Talis River
description:
The crystal waters of this river come from the plains and mountains to
the north as clear and gelid as any in Shalar.  By the time they reach
southern Cimar, they've taken a slightly amber hue, and are noticeably
more opaque than at the northern end of town, but are still relatively
clean and healthy waters.  The tiny bubbles and distortions in the
water's seemingly peaceful surface belie the illusion of placidity by
speeding downstream at an impressive pace.  Near the South Bridge, the
water finally begins to stir, and as it reaches the southern portcullis,
it tumbles into rapids as it topples over a waterfall to crash into the
ocean's shore below.  A bridge crosses the water directly to your south.

name: Blackeye Falls
description:
The gargantuan outer walls of Cimar open here, and a massive gateway allows
the Talis River to flow through and crash down the cliff into the red sea
below.  there is no grate over the opening and it is quite a long drop
with little to catch hold of at this point.  There is a portcullis far over
your head, but it is drawn up into the wall and useless for catching anything
on the river.  The waters of the river move very swiftly here, yet seem very
smooth in their motion, flowing over the edge in a gradual arc.  To either
side, you see the disorienting size of the outer walls stretching along the
shore, atop the massive red cliffs of Cimar.  Above, the wall blots out half
the sky, and below, the water falls thirty feet to the rocky shore.

description:

below.  there is no grate over the opening and it is quite a long drop
with little to catch hold of at this point.  There is a portcullis far over
your head, but it is drawn up into the wall and useless for catching anything
on the river.  The waters of the river move very swiftly here, yet seem very
smooth in their motion, flowing over the edge in a gradual arc.  To either
side, you see the disorienting size of the outer walls stretching along the
shore, atop the massive red cliffs of Cimar.  Above, the wall blots out half
the sky, and below, the water falls thirty feet to the rocky shore.

name: A Rickety Bridge
description:
A few wide planks bridge the Talis River here, forming a wobbly walkway
over the rapidly running water.  You note, with a vested interest in your
own health, that these boards upon which you tread are indeed firmly
anchored to either shore.  They certainly don't feel like it as you stand,
helplessly bobbing up and down, out of reach of any solid land.  To your
north, the inner wall of Cimar is punctured by an arching waterway gap, and
you can see through it that the river runs in a north-northeast direction
for the length of the city.  This bridge serves to keep New Cimar connected
across the river, but isn't quite the marvel of modern engineering that the
rest of Cimar's bridges are.  South of here, the river drops out of sight
over the edge of a cliff.

name: The Cityguard Compound
description:
A small bunker-type building nestled in the shadows of the gargantuan outer
wall of Cimar, the cityguard compound is more of a dungeon than a proper
headquarters for a law-keeping force.  This building, on the very boundary of
Old Cimar, gives the impression of being quite a lot older than its
surroundings in this sector of the city.  It looks to have been built around
the same time as the inner wall itself.  The wooden tables and chairs and lack
of any sort of decorative or functional touch-ups make it seem as though the
actual \headquarters\" is mobile

name: The Back Room
description:
This tiny room in the dungeon-like bunker the cityguards have appropriated
serves as the entrance to a very disgruntled anti-paladin guild.  A very
cramped space, it has a small door leading west into what was until recently
an abandoned stone building, and a trap door to a stone staircase which
descends into a forgotten basement.  Gelid air billows up from the stairs,
blanketing the area in a chilling wind.  Looking around, you see that the
cityguards have deigned to use this room as a broom closet and storage for
their rusty armor and weapons.  Peering down the stairwell, it is possible to
see the dim flicker of torchlight, and to hear the sound of heavy footsteps
moving around.

name: The Grinning Devil Bar
description:
The soft yellow light from a torch in the corner plays on the features of
this room.  The spiraling stone staircase at one side of the room creates
huge, disfigured shadows on the wall opposite the torch;  ghastly phantoms of
darkness, silently leaping back and forth through the air.  Flickering light
also touches on a large bar made of the same stone as the rest of the ancient
building.  It looks as though this mound of stones was originally some sort of
table.  And, given the cryptlike appearance of this underground catacomb, it
would be a safe assumption that the \table\" was

area_id: or casket.  And now it's being used as a bar.  Truly an anti-paladin abode.

name: A Dank Hallway
description:
This short hallway is at the back of a tiny building the cityguards use as
their headquarters.  The building is packed into the shadow of Cimar's massive
outer wall, and slightly below the Talis River's water level.  As a result, it
is a very dark, wet, cold place.  You can see your breath in the air here, and
hear little but your footsteps clattering against the stone floor along with
those of several rats.  To the north and west, steel bar doors lead to tiny
jail cells, and to the east, the main room of the cityguard headquarters
awaits.  South of here, the outer wall of Cimar actually serves as the wall of
this building as well.  Nobody seems worried that any occupants of the cell to
the west might claw their way through and fall thirty feet to the ocean.

name: A Tiny Cell
description:
Dark and dank, as you might expect a jail cell to be, the wet stone floor of
this cramped room sends chills through the air.  The walls are made of roughly
hewn stone cemented in place by heavy mortar and rusting iron strut supports.
No windows grace the cell's walls, and the only source of light is through the
cityguard headquarters.  Tiny reflections of light from the outside make it
this far into the building, bouncing from pools of filthy water on the floor
outside the cell.  You hear the sound of dozens of tiny rat feet scurrying
about, and the occasional raised voice from another cell or elsewhere in this
compound.  Aside from those, the only noise that meets your ears is the
constant dripping of water.

name: A Tiny Cell
description:
Dark and dank, as you might expect a jail cell to be, the wet stone floor of
this cramped room sends chills through the air.  The walls are made of roughly

compound.  Aside from those, the only noise that meets your ears is the
constant dripping of water.

name: New Cimar
description:
You stand in the strip of homes and plots of land between Cimar's outer
and inner walls.  It's known as New Cimar in polite circles, and sometimes
as Leechtown or Fungusville in impolite ones.  It houses some of the lesser
families of Cimar, in their smaller homes and less extravagant businesses,
but also holds in its confines the powerful and world-renown mage guilds of
Cimar and the highly trained Cimarrite Army.  For now, though, these things
are at the back of your mind as you kick your way through the litter and
debris.  To the north, an arch in the inner wall leads to Old Cimar, and east
of that, the wall makes ready to cross the Talis River by way of a grand
arch.  To your east, a small bridge crosses the river, and to the west stands
the cityguard headquarters.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  To the south, the inner wall of Cimar separates the old city
from New Cimar, and a large gate opens in its expansive length to allow
Wormwood Avenue to pass through.  The sound of the river is quite loud here,
as it nears the waterfall at its southern end.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  A bit to the south, Wormwood passes through a large gate in
Cimar's inner wall, and joins New Cimar.  To the west, a worn path intersects
with the avenue and runs just to the south of an ancient grove in the center
of the city.  North of here, Wormwood Avenue continues its winding way.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  To the west, you may enter a small grove of very old trees at
the center of the city.  To the east and south, Wormwood Avenue continues its
windings through the heart of Old Cimar.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  A ways to the west, you see a tightly-packed grove of ancient
trees in the center of Old Cimar, and a worn path leading around it.  North
of here, Wormwood Avenue continues on its way toward Kost Square, twisting
its way through Cimar.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  To the west, you see the side of a tightly packed grove of
trees, while Wormwood Avenue continues its winding ways to the north and
south.  Here, a grate in the road toward the edge of the cobbling draws your
attention.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  A little ways to the north, across Rantid Road, Kost Square's
darker corners bustle quietly with all manner of black market items and
shady characters making unpalatable bargains.  Directly to your east and
south, you can continue to walk around the square along the meandering
avenue.

name: A Worn Path
description:
This road had a name, centuries ago.  At some point between its naming in
the original settlement and Cimar's expansion into the huge city it is today,
the last man who had that name locked away beyond some barrier of poor memory
passed on to the afterlife.  And so, as its cobblestones have faded into
nothingness, so has the memory of this path's place in the city's history.
Now, it is part of a tiny core of untouched, undeveloped land at Cimar's
center;  a tightly banded grove of ancient trees, a small pond, and this
dirty old path are the sole remnant of the original Cimarrite trade town,
built upon the ruins of an even more ancient city.

description:

name: A Small Grove of Trees
description:
This tiny forest at Cimar's center is all that remains of what was once a
great forest.  Now huddled between busy streets like Rantid Road and the
bustling business district to the west, it slowly withers away over the
decades before the steadily approaching tide of civilization.  Only rangers
make their home here now, toiling to keep this last bastion of the forest safe
from hands who would destroy it.  From here, you can see the inner wall of
Cimar to the west.  You can hear the bustle of Rantid Road to the north, and
the sound of the polluted Talis River to the east.  The occasional scream
rings out from the dungeon-like jail at the citugard headquarters on the other
side of the inner wall to the south, but it is mercifully muffled by the
trees.

name: A Small Grove of Trees
description:

great forest.  Now huddled between busy streets like Rantid Road and the

rings out from the dungeon-like jail at the citugard headquarters on the other
side of the inner wall to the south, but it is mercifully muffled by the
trees.

name: The Outpost
description:
A tiny wooden shack stands here, with a small stone firepit just outside.
Smoke curls up and around the roof of the shanty, filling the area with the
scent of burning wood and cooking meat.  A tree stump to one side has been
hollowed out and looks to be used as a chair.  A few bushes have bits of
leather hanging from their branches, drying in the sun.  To the north and
west, a beautiful grove grows, the center of the tiny forest which is itself
the center of Cimar.  East and south of here, the forest continues.  Above
you, a large hole in the leaf cover opens, and the sky is visible;  tendrils
of smoke from the fire waft up to join the clouds.  The ground here is worn
through to dirt, and packed hard.  You are as far from Cimar as it is possible
to be, at the city's center.

name: A Small Grove of Trees
description:
This tiny forest at Cimar's center is all that remains of what was once a
great forest.  Now huddled between busy streets like Rantid Road and the
bustling business district to the west, it slowly withers away over the

rings out from the dungeon-like jail at the citugard headquarters on the other
side of the inner wall to the south, but it is mercifully muffled by the
trees.

name: The Ancient Oak
description:
In this part of the grove, a large clearing has been opened, almost as if
the trees now at its edge hold a reverence for the massive, gnarled old oak at
its center.  It is impossible to discern the oak's age simply by looking at
it;  its bark is deeply creased and very thick, and moss grows over almost
every square inch.  To the west, the grove continues, and to the south, a
small outpost is set up within the tiny forest.  East and north of here, the
trees have grown too closely together to see much beyond them;  almost like a
wall against the civilized outside.  The oak tree at the center of this area
rises up like a titan, its branches spread out like massive arms and blanket
the entire clearing in an ethereal green glow.

name: A Lonesome Grove
description:
The saddest songs heard in bars around Cimar are sung of the Heart of Kost.
A huge grove of trees at the very center of the city, the Heart was lovingly
tended to by each and every citizen of that ancient metropolis.  It was
considered to be that which held Kost's walls against a thousand armies, which
led the city to thousands of years of prosperity, which made the gods smile
down upon Shalar.  And then, in the Great War, it was lost.  This tiny
collection of venerable trees, tightly banded in the center of Old Cimar, is
all that remains of the once-thriving Heart of Kost.  Up against Cimar's inner
wall and only a few feet from its bustling business district, civilization is
closing in on all sides.  None of the citizens care for it enough to let it
thrive again, and only the rangers who live here now tend to it at all.

name: A Quiescent Pond
description:
Here, the grove at Cimar's center opens, and a small pond lies serenely
between hillocks covered with lush, green grass.  The trees grow on all sides,
very thickly in places -- almost like a wall -- and only a few small breezes
make their way through to dance politely across the surface of the water.
With a dainty ripple here and a delicate ruffle there, the glasslike pond is
disturbed only occasionally.  Very few large animals venture this far into the
city, but those that do discover a perfect watering hole.  Many small animals
live their entire lives in this grove, and birds of all sizes wash themselves
at the water's edge.  East of here, a small outpost rests between the trees,
and to the north, the grove continues.  Over the wall beyond the trees to the
west, you hear the busy business district of Cimar.

name: A Hidden Attic
description:
This tight space is not something one would expect to find in Cimar's
palace;  particularly not directly above its throne room.  It is unlit, but
from the light that streams in around the door above you, you can see
rather well.  The room is indeed cramped, but in one small indulgence, the
palace's architect has created it from the same rare white marble which
makes up the rest of the extravagant building.  A few drops of wax here and
there make it clear to you that this passage is occasionally used (and the
way lit with a candle), though it has not been in some time judging by the
coating of dust on top of the dried droplets.  Perhaps it is an escape
route which has been forgotten after years of peace in the city.

name: The Cimarrite Throne
description:
The flat white marble surfaces of the rest of the palace can't compare to
what this room has to offer.  Here, at the throne, intricately carved
statues and columns line the walls, and the entire floor appears to be one
large slab etched with a highly detailed map of Shalar.  The throne itself
is also constructed of white marble, a lace-like latticework of designs
which seems so feathery and light that it couldn't support a man's weight -
and yet, it is where the king sits daily to dispense his wisdom and
rulings.  At the top of the elaborate chair perches a stylized boar with a
too-large head and huge teeth, its glistening marble tusks protruding
perhaps a bit farther than they should.  To the east, a blindingly white
archway leads to the main room of the palace.

name: The Palace of Cimar
description:
Brilliant white marble makes up every surface of this palace.  A mirrored
ceiling reflects you and everything around you from above, and the marble
surfaces all around provide more reflective surfaces to confuse your eye.
Aside from the throne gates to the west and large portraits to the north and
south, there are no features in the area to counter the bright swirling stone
which comprises both floor and walls.  Your footsteps clatter noisily
against the polished floor and echo for what seems an eternity, finally
slipping into silence.  The edges of the marble blocks which make up the
walls are elaborately gilded, while the floor is simply solid white.
Attractive candle formations and intricate crystal chandeliers keep the
room well lit, and the entire place is a reminder of the riches of Cimar's
highest seat.

name: The Palace of Cimar
description:
Brilliant white marble makes up every surface of this palace.  A mirrored
ceiling reflects you and everything around you from above, and the marble
surfaces all around provide more reflective surfaces to confuse your eye.
Aside from the palace gates to the east and hallways to the north and south,
there are no features in the area to counter the bright swirling stone
which comprises both floor and walls.  Your footsteps clatter noisily
against the polished floor and echo for what seems an eternity, finally
slipping into silence.  The edges of the marble blocks which make up the
walls are elaborately gilded, while the floor is simply solid white.

room well lit, and the entire place is a reminder of the riches of Cimar's

name: A Guardroom
description:
A tiny, cramped space, this guardroom is where the palace holds its reserve
forces.  Those who are on their shift currently sit playing card games and
chatting, fully realizing that there's no way any conflict will reach the
palace without their being made fully aware.  Cimar is impregnable.  Each
corner of the palace holds a room just like this one;  a table in its center,
where guards eat their meals and rest their helmets, playing games and making
conversation, a small weapons rack near the door with brand new swords and
shields, and a small stone spiral staircase leading up to a tower above.

name: The Southwest Pinnacle
description:
This pinnacle, along with the three others which protrude from the palace's
rooftop, is the highest point in Cimar.  The palace itself is founded upon
the foothills of Mount Cim, and these towers add another twenty feet in
height.  You can look down on the temple of High Cimar, the towers of the
Mage Block to the southeast, the tallest of masts in the harbor, and you can
even peek over the top of the massive outer wall to the northeast and spy on
the outlying village of Koteras.  Looking through the western windows of this
tower, you see forests and stones at eye level.  As tall as your tower is,
Mount Cim stretches on out of your field of vision, as if to assert its place
over any man-made structure.

name: The Palace Gates
description:
The gates of the palace of Cimar are made of massive wooden slats pressed
together and held with riveted iron bands.  They have been age-worn to a
smooth finish, and look to be heavy enough to hold off a small army once
someone manages to close them.  The sides of the gates which face High Cimar
are unadorned, and since they remain perpetually open, it is unconcernedly so
that they are not decorative.  The sides which face the palace's interior,
however, are inlaid with a patchwork of gold and ivory, obsidian, and a few
jewels toward the center;  all thrown together into a breathtaking likeness
of a mighty boar, the symbol of Cimar's power.  To the east, High Cimar's
glittering streets and bright green groves stand high above the rest of the
city.

name: The Temple of High Cimar
description:
In high gothic style architecture, this layered room stands forty feet
into the sky at its apex.  Staring up to the uppermost point of the
cavernous vaulted ceiling, you can't quite be sure how steep the sides are.
It could be nearly flat, or it could stretch on up for a mile - your depth
perception is severely skewed by your perspective.  You notice a modest
wooden stairwell leading up one corner of the chamber, first past the huge
columns on the bottom level, then stretching on beyond the smaller columns
above that, and finally passing the ornate frescoes and stained glass
windows at the top level.  It leads to a small balcony at the very top of
the room, where a few priests seem to be congregating.  Several pulpits are
set up in this room;  one from which to preach each sort of religion, one
might assume.

name: The Western Temple
description:
Rows and rows of pews cover the floor here, places to sit and worship on
holy days - and kindling in more than one anti-paladin raid.  Thirty foot
high stained glass windows depicting scenes from the Great War cover the
western wall, while paladins of renown are enshrined in colored glass
likenesses to the north and south.  The names of the gods of light are
emblazoned upon marble busts below the windows, and highly elaborate
scrollwork and carvings decorate the entire area.  Columns rise up out of
the floor, jutting through the air like smooth, civilized stalagmites to
join the ceiling high above.  And the ceiling... the massive vaulted style
in this wing is a smaller version of what can be seen in the main chamber
to the east, but no less impressive.

name: The Paladin's Abode
description:
Orderly, virtuous and dedicated, the average paladin and his personality
are accurately reflected in Cimar's paladin guild.  A member of the chapter
might have a seat at a plain wooden table next to a clear pane glass
window, eating a bowl of hot soup or a helping of fish caught in the red
sea to the south.  He might look out that same window to the streets of
High Cimar, to watch for wrongdoings or evil, or simply to contemplate the
blessing of life as evident in the moving, working, living city below.  A
rack of gleaming shields, armor, swords, and maces seems to be the only
thing in this place not made of simple wooden slats and poles.

name: The Eastern Temple
description:
Rows and rows of pews cover the floor here, places to sit and worship on
holy days - and kindling in more than one anti-paladin raid.  Thirty foot
high stained glass windows depicting scenes from the Great War cover the
eastern wall, while zealots of renown are enshrined in colored glass
likenesses to the north and south.  The names of the gods of light and
darkness are emblazoned upon marble busts below the windows, and highly
elaborate scrollwork and carvings decorate the entire area.  Columns rise
up out of the floor, jutting through the air like smooth, civilized
stalagmites to join the ceiling high above.  And the ceiling... the massive
vaulted style in this wing is a smaller version of what can be seen in the
main chamber to the west, but no less impressive.

name: The Sojourn
description:
All around this room, candles of various colors exude various odors and
burn at various lengths.  Puddles of wax coat every shelf.  Each religious
zealot who comes through this guildhall lights a candle in some symbolic
showing or another, and each of them believes deeply that it is a great
gesture in worship of his or her god of choice.  To be blessed for the
coming days would be a great thing, and every highly religious priest in
this guild knows the importance of having a god on his side.  Symbols have
been drawn all over the flat surfaces of the room, culminating in a huge
pentagram which takes up nearly all the floor space.  Vicious weapons and
elaborately decorated armor dangle from hooks and pegs everywhere, and
droplets of the blood of the sacreligious and heretical prove to be the
only thing marring any of it.

name: The Upper Monastery
description:
Almost like a bell tower, this balcony area resides in the huge vaulted
ceiling of the main chamber of High Cimar's temple.  Looking over the
railed edge, you stare down a significant distance to the ground floor of
the cathedral.  Peering at the rows of pews and gothic columns from this
vantage point, you are struck by not only their beauty, but also by their
stately order.  This upper level balcony is constructed of modest wooden
beams which creak when trodden upon, yet seem perfectly solid, being
anchored to the granite walls of the temple.  Up this high, the light from
the stained glass windows below provides a surreal glow of colored warmth
from underneath your feet.

name: The Cloister
description:
A quiet, reflective place, this guild is where Cimar's healers come to
pay homage to their lords and ladies, and to contemplate the happenings of
the day.  Gorgeous wood panels, varnished and kept shining in the low
lamplight, adorn each wall.  The ceiling, an awe-inspiring vaulted affair
featuring an intricately painted rendition of the Shalaran star chart
which some priests use to locate their source of power, is an imposing and
impressive sight.  All manner of chairs are scattered about the room, from
large, comfortable divans to flat straw mats on the dusty floor.  This
place is very quiet, like most of the rest of the temple of High Cimar, and
you sense that to disturb such a thing would be as sacreligious as an anti-
paladin's presence.

name: The Cimar Library
description:
You stand in the midst of the incredible library of Cimar, whose renown
far precedes it.  It is said that this very room contains every book written
in Shalar since the Great War, and no small number of those volumes which were
written before it.  It is a quiet place, and scholarly people sit and study in
almost complete silence;  the only noise you can make out here is from outside
the temple of High Cimar.  Some of the sounds from Cimar's business district
waft up this high, and the singing masts of the city's harbor are barely
audible, yet add a distinct color to the overall sonority in the air.  Turning
your full attention back to the books by which you are surrounded, you see a
series of massive bookshelves directly before you and to each side.

name: The Common Guild Recruitment Area
description:
A fairly busy room, the recruitment area is alive with all different
manner of people.  There are a few aristocratic looking hobnobbers, looking
down their noses at the local recruitment officer for the guild, and a
small group of ruddy-looking folk gathered around him and gazing reverently
at his flowing tan robes.  To these people, the poor and the needy, those
tan robes are a sign of acceptance and safety;  any Common Guild recruiter
is fairly quickly made one of the most popular people in the area.  This
recruiter ignores the buffed warriors and shiningly wealthy merchant-types
who give him no second glance, and kindly focuses his attention on those
who have a definite interest in what he has to say...

name: High Cimar
description:
The streets of High Cimar are lined with gold, so the saying goes.  While
they don't appear in person to be made of gold, exactly, they are awfully
expensive-looking.  Cobbled with rare and costly black granite and cemented
by silver dust mortar from the mountains to the north, this road alone must
have cost a fortune.  All around you on this stretch of land are beautifully
maintained groves of trees and flowers, plant life stretching the entire
length of the district.  There are no private homes in High Cimar;  rather,
only the temple - which houses the holy guilds and the Cimarrite library -
and the palace of Cimar itself.  To your south, the city of Cimar reaches its
massive fingers out to the reddish sea, down a gradual slope.  To the west,
the city's palace stands magnificent as the highest point in Cimar.

you see why exactly High Cimar is so high - the foothills of Mount Cim
provide impressive elevation.

name: The High Wood
description:
Groves of beautifully maintained trees line the section of this city
known as High Cimar.  As this corner of the city climbs slowly up the
foothills of Mount Cim, it rises into the sky toward the peak of the
mountain and away from the salty air of the ocean to the south.  Trees
flourish here, healthy and strong, and the correct shade of green.  Far
from the pollution of the decrepit sections of the city, regal High Cimar
is awash in cleanliness, decency, and beauty which is rivaled in few other
cities.  To the north and west, the black granite cobble of High Cimar
awaits, and to the east, more of the High Wood flourishes.  To your
immediate south, the inner wall of Cimar separates High Cimar from the old
city.  Off to the west, you see Cimar's palace at the city's highest point.

name: High Temple Square
description:
The epicenter of Shalaran religion, according to some, High Cimar's temple
certainly stands as a gorgeous beacon of a reminder;  Shalar's pantheon will
not be ignored or forgotten any time soon.  Here, to its south, you stand in
the High Temple Square, where you can marvel at the temple's construction.
Flaring out to either side of the building, spidery buttresses fly as if
wings, lifting the temple itself above the rest of the city.  Stained glass
windows stretch up to the clouds, appearing by way of your perspective to
out-heighten even the massive outer walls.  The windows depict glorious
scenes of battle, and multiple heavenly countenances which become more and
more recognizable as the windows deign to near the filthy ground.  Columns
and statues, all carved in an intricate style, lend to the building's art.

name: A Rubbly Path
description:
This section of the inner wall was broken down long ago.  As to what might
have done it, you can only speculate.  You can see that, from the way the
wall itself is constructed, as one continuous whole, it would be a very large
job indeed to correct this small gap.  And thus, it's gone a very long time
without being fixed, it seems.  The inner wall certainly isn't as important
to the city as the outer wall;  the massive outer walls could hold off any
force, while the inner walls are more of a landmark from the first days of
Old Cimar.  Everyone from aristocrats to messengers to members of the
royal family uses this sloping \path

room_id: and creates a very convenient shortcut from the

name: The Highgate
description:
Once the titanic outer walls of Cimar were built, the inner wall had far
less strategic significance.  On the 1000th anniversary of the fall of Kost,
the gate here was torn down and replaced with a work of art.  This plot of
land had served as home to Old Cimar's northern gate for hundreds of years,
but when it no longer had a defensive function for the city, great architects
were called from all over the region to design a tribute to the city's
longevity.  This gorgeous and elegant arching tower of ivory was the result.
So much like lace, it seems as though it should not capable of supporting
itself as a free-standing structure;  yet, it has stood centuries more since
its construction.  To the south, it's a short walk along Toller Road to Kost
Square, and to the north it is only a few dozen feet to the temple of High
Cimar.

and the palace of Cimar itself.  To your south, the city of Cimar reaches its
massive fingers out to the reddish sea, down a gradual slope.  To the west,
you see why exactly High Cimar is so high - the foothills of Mount Cim
provide impressive elevation.

name: High Avenue
description:
The crisp lines of High Avenue stretch off to the north, through the
grand gates of Cimar and into the village of Koteras at the city's edge.
To the west, you stare directly into the heart of High Cimar.  Beyond a
temple where Cimarrite citizens may worship the god of their choice, the
grounds climb up the foothills of Mount Cim and the palace is perched at
the city's highest point.  This road is in a high state of repair, well
maintained by the bulk of the city's public works funds.  Whether it's a
matter of personal vanity or a sense for the city's well being, the king
considers this stretch of land to be very important;  travelers should
always be impressed by the beauty of High Cimar.  And indeed, lined by
groves of trees and cobbled with black granite, High Avenue perpetuates
that image.

name: High Avenue
description:
The crisp lines of High Avenue stretch off to the north, through the grand
gates of Cimar and into the village of Koteras at the city's edge.  To the
west, you stare directly into the heart of High Cimar.  Beyond a temple where
Cimarrite citizens may worship the god of their choice, the grounds climb up

of the city's public works funds.  Whether it's a matter of personal vanity
or a sense for the city's well being, the king considers this stretch of land
to be very important;  travelers should always be impressed by the beauty of
High Cimar.  And indeed, lined by groves of trees and cobbled with black
granite, High Avenue perpetuates that image.

name: The Great Northern Gate
description:
The gargantuan double-peaked gate at the northern end of Cimar is a larger
and less elaborate version of the Highgate, put in place to instill a sense of
awe in approaching travellers, yet still functional as a defensive
emplacement.  The huge gates themselves tower over every building in High
Cimar.  It takes a team of horses to haul them open and shut during a battle.
In the last few hundred years, there have been fewer and fewer armies to
attempt to siege Cimar;  the gates have settled into their place in the open
position.  All around you, the beauty of Cimar is stunning and overwhelming.
This entire section of the city is built upon the foothills of Mount Cim to
the west, and is elevated above the rest.  You look down on everything in
Cimar from here, and it seems like a beautiful place.

name: The High Wood
description:
Groves of beautifully maintained trees line the section of this city
known as High Cimar.  As this corner of the city climbs slowly up the
foothills of Mount Cim, it rises into the sky toward the peak of the
mountain and away from the salty air of the ocean to the south.  Trees
flourish here, healthy and strong, and the correct shade of green.  Far
from the pollution of the decrepit sections of the city, regal High Cimar
is awash in cleanliness, decency, and beauty which is rivaled in few other
cities.  To the west, High Avenue streaks out the north gate, and a ways to
the south, Toller Road drives its way east and west.  Off to the west, you
see the temple of High Cimar, and beyond that Cimar's palace at the city's
highest point.

name: The High Wood
description:
Groves of beautifully maintained trees line the section of this city
known as High Cimar.  As this corner of the city climbs slowly up the
foothills of Mount Cim, it rises into the sky toward the peak of the
mountain and away from the salty air of the ocean to the south.  Trees
flourish here, healthy and strong, and the correct shade of green.  Far
from the pollution of the decrepit sections of the city, regal High Cimar
is awash in cleanliness, decency, and beauty which is rivaled in few other
cities.  To the west, High Avenue streaks out the north gate, and to the
south, Toller Road drives its way east and west.  Off to the west, you see
the temple of High Cimar, and beyond that Cimar's palace at the city's
highest point.

name: The Bank of Cimar
description:
Gorgeous multicolored marble tiles cover the walls and floor of this
building, and the ceiling is a huge black slate slab.  To one side, you see
off-white marble with gold veins of color, and below you you see black with
ghostly gray stripes.  A desk stretches across the length of the room, an
obsidian top perched upon a stand of gold-flecked bricks.  This is where the
riches of Cimar reside;  the bank of the largest city on the continent.  Just
below the black-as-pitch tabletop, you see a sign detailing the banking
process.  Through an open door to the south, you see the traffic of West
Toller Road bustling by.  Given the highly public placement of this building,
it would be a reasonable assumption that your money will be safe here.

name: An Auction Stand
description:
A large wooden podium atop a grandstand looms quietly here, at the north end
of Kost Square.  This area is reserved for auctions, and thus traffic is a bit
less daunting.  It is considered rude to pass through an auction in progress
on your way from place to place.  Strewn around the auction grounds are small
pieces of paper;  each has printed upon it a price, a number, a secret
communique from bidder to bidder, a list of items, some sort of auction-
related tidbit of information.  Apparently the grounds haven't been cleaned
since the last auction.  A wind blows through, and momentarily a blizzard of
varicolored papers swirls about you in a blinding whirlwind.

name: West Toller Road
description:
The main street in Cimar, Toller Road runs its entire width from east to
west.  The road is narrower here than in the eastern half of the city, as
most traffic moves through the north and east gates.  But you still find
yourself surrounded by a large number of citygoers, from businessmen and
merchants to fairly obvious thieves and purse snatchers.  While there isn't
much traffic moving directly through the city here, there is quite a lot
between the business district in Cimar's southwest quadrant and other parts
of the city.  This part of Toller Road is in Old Cimar, running parallel with
the inner wall to the north.  Lined on both sides by private homes and
branched from by several north-to-south avenues, it bustles with activity
through most of the day.  To the north stands the Bank of Cimar.

name: Kost Square
description:
You stand at the western edge of Kost Square - the location which most
would say is the center of Cimar both geographically and commercially.
All around you, people hustle back and forth with goods.  Chickens and
geese seem to roam freely here, while most larger livestock you see are
on tethers of some sort.  Most.  Kost Square is certainly Cimar's
busiest point, and there is little way for anyone to dispute that
claim.  This square has taken such a firm hold on Cimar that any roads
which run through it become nameless and meaningless.  The traffic goes
through however it can, running side to side and looping around carts
and kiosks in such a manner that much of what comes into Kost Square
doesn't leave in the correct direction for a very long time.  At the
center of the area, a strange black monolith towers.

name: Kost Square
description:
You stand at the center of Kost Square - the location which most
would say is the center of Cimar both geographically and commercially.
All around you, people hustle back and forth with goods.  Chickens and
geese seem to roam freely here, while most larger livestock you see are

busiest point, and there is little way for anyone to dispute that
claim.  This square has taken such a firm hold on Cimar that any roads
which run through it become nameless and meaningless.  The traffic goes
through however it can, running side to side and looping around carts
and kiosks in such a manner that much of what comes into Kost Square
doesn't leave in the correct direction for a very long time.

name: An Intersection
description:
This is quite possibly the most convoluted intersection of roads in
Cimar.  It is at the northeastern corner of Kost Square, which is a
complicated place on its own, and three major roads intersect here.
Running in from the east, Toller Road blunders straight into a small
fence, and half of it shears off to continue into the western section of
Cimar.  From the south, Wormwood Avenue tangles its way through Old Cimar
and finally flares into nonexistence at an indeterminate point somewhere
near here, with one last twist through and around the square.  And,
thrusting out from the chaos off to the north, a perfectly straight and
beautifully maintained road is born into High Cimar and moves directly
out the north gate as though disgusted by its confused peers.

name: East Toller Road
description:
This is the main road in Cimar, running east and west its entire length.
A ways to the east lies the North Bridge, which crosses the Talis River.
To your north, you can see a pleasant grove of trees, while to your west
you can hear more than see a huge, busy intersection.  The road is wide
here to facilitate major traffic, and you can move to the south to avoid
the carriages which normally inhabit this half of the road.  Bustling
traffic buffets you from all sides here as business moves in and out of
the city, and from sector to sector.  Keep moving, or pay the price and
be buried alive beneath a mountain of sweaty, hurrying flesh.

name: East Toller Road
description:
This is the main road in Cimar, running east and west its entire length.
A ways to the east lies the North Bridge, which crosses the Talis River.
The road is wide here to facilitate major traffic, and you can move to
the north to avoid the carriages which normally inhabit this half of the
road.  To your west, a huge intersection noisily does what intersections
do best, and to the south lies a roughly north-south road.  Bustling
traffic buffets you from all sides here as business moves in and out of
the city, and from sector to sector.  Keep moving, or pay the price and
be buried alive beneath a mountain of sweaty, hurrying flesh.

name: East Toller Road
description:
This is the main road in Cimar, running east and west its entire length.
Just to the east lies the North Bridge, which crosses the Talis River.
The road is wide here to facilitate major traffic, and you can move to
the north to avoid the carriages which sometimes inhabit this half of the
road.  A ways off to your west, a huge intersection noisily does what
intersections do best, and to the north Toller Road widens out.  Bustling
traffic buffets you from all sides here as business moves in and out of
the city, and from sector to sector.  Keep moving, or pay the price and
be buried alive beneath a mountain of sweaty, hurrying flesh.

would say is the center of Cimar both geographically and commercially.
All around you, people hustle back and forth with goods.  Chickens and

name: The Black Market
description:
The traffic of Kost Square thins out a bit here.  There are a few
frightening looking men standing about, barring passage into and out of this
area of the square.  You see all manner of shadiness here, from thieves,
purse snatchers, and cat burglars, to rogues, brigands, and hired killers.
The clink of gold in purses is practically deafening as it rolls in from the
south, while the deathly quiet from the west is equally distracting.  East
and north of here, the normal business of Kost Square goes about its daily
routine;  this seems to be the southeast corner of Cimar's center, but to
have been commandeered somehow.

name: A Dark Corner of Kost Square
description:
Darting back and forth here, messengers and trained killers speed from place
to place.  This area of Kost Square is remarkably busy, but also strangely
hushed.  The activity here is more subdued, almost as if anticipating a spring
into action;  the movement visible in other parts of the square is far noisier
and less restrained.  Suddenly, it becomes blatantly obvious:  this is Cimar's
assassin guild.  The ultimate assassin guild, in fact, for it has no set base
of operations and no one guildmaster.  Looking around, you see half a dozen
men staring at you.  Any one of them might be ready to train you in the finer
arts of killing... or to kill you.

name: The Busy Corner
description:
It seems as though every man, woman and child standing at this corner of
Kost Square has a purse the size of his head or larger, and a smirk set
permanently upon his face.  Barricaded on all sides by racks and makeshift
walls, and guarded by burly men being paid to be present, this area serves as
the thief's guild of Cimar.  You see many grand master thieves lurking about,
training the younger, inexperienced pickpockets;  watching the students dash
out into the crowded square to the north to weave their way in and out of the
throng of citizens and return with a sack full of loot, the guildmaster
remains innocent while his reputation as a teacher grows, along with the gold
in his pockets.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  Here, at its hazy origin, it is born out of the
confusion of a mangled intersection to the north and the busy commerce
of Kost Square to the west.  In that area, roads have no names... there
is merely a large amorphous shape done in streets from which sprout
individuals which then take on identity.  Wormwood Avenue is one such
road.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even spins through
the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and landmarks.  From
here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam of some
sort.  To the north, Toller Road makes ready to smash into Kost Square.
To your west, Kost Square itself resides, and to the south you can
continue along Wormwood Avenue.

name: Wormwood Avenue
description:
This charming road winds its way through Old Cimar in a vaguely north
to south direction.  It curves and winds, bends and in some cases even
spins through the inner city, visiting guilds and shops, homes and
landmarks.  From here, you can see the Talis River to your east, over a dam
of some sort.  A little ways to the northwest, Kost Square's darker corners
bustle quietly with all manner of black market items and shady characters
making unpalatable bargains.  Directly to your north and west, you can
continue to walk around the square along the meandering avenue.

description:

name: West Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has
expanded, and since the advent of highways and trade routes, Rantid Road
has fallen into a state of relative disuse.  Compared with the incredible
traffic of Toller Road, this street is calm and picturesque.  The
cobblestones making up the road are worn and cracked at the edges, and make
a uniform surface of smoothed stone.  In the center, the cobblestones have
come entirely away in many places, revealing occasional glimpses at the
ancient slate pathways which preceded even Old Cimar.  Rantid Road
continues to the east, across the South Bridge and away from the center of
Old Cimar.  The expansive road lies both west and south of you, and a road
branches off to the north.

name: West Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has
expanded, and since the advent of highways and trade routes, Rantid Road

ancient slate pathways which preceded even Old Cimar.  Rantid Road
continues to the east, across the South Bridge and away from the center of
Old Cimar.  To the west, Rantid Road trails off and gives way to a winding
avenue.

name: West Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has
expanded, and since the advent of highways and trade routes, Rantid Road
has fallen into a state of relative disuse.  Compared with the incredible
traffic of Toller Road, this street is calm and picturesque.  The
cobblestones making up the road are worn and cracked at the edges, and make
a uniform surface of smoothed stone.  In the center, the cobblestones have

ancient slate pathways which preceded even Old Cimar.  Rantid Road
continues to the east, across the South Bridge and away from the center of
Old Cimar.  South of here, Wormwood Avenue branches off.

name: The End of Rantid Road
description:
Here, Rantid Road meets an unceremonious end.  This was once the main road
of Cimar, during the days of the original settlers, and helped to found a
great city on the rubble that was Kost.  It appears as though the road once
led through the inner wall here, and out into the west;  since the city's
expansion, however, the wall has been sealed here, and the road simply ends.
The inner wall of Cimar, seen up close, is impressive -- yet, being a wall
which is more than a millenium old, it shows its age.  Worn by weather, by
ancient battles, by sun and by mischief, it stands as if a tooth which, while
once a great fang, has been worn to dull uselessness.  To the north, a space
between the wall and a home opens out as the wall has broken down there;  to
the east, the road continues across Old Cimar.

name: West Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has

name: West Rantid Road
description:
This street was once called Main Street by the original Cimarrite
settlers, and runs through the heart of Old Cimar.  Since the city has
expanded, and since the advent of highways and trade routes, Rantid Road
